<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-012-520  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 012 520.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIS Week  Jan 1 1990 v11 n1 p12(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>MIS managers look to the '90s. (management information systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Adler, Bart; Alexander, John J.; Reddy, Jim.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Management information managers foresee the emergence of maturestandards in the 1990s in hardware, software and local areanetworks that will allow applications to be developed independentof hardware or network structures.andP;  Database vendors will be morecompetitive on price and performance with the emergence ofstandards such as Structured Query Language operating on differentoperating systems and hardware platforms.andP;  Standards will make itless likely that organizations will become dependent on any onevendor's products.andP;  In other areas, fiber optics technology willbecome increasingly important in the 1990s, in wide area networks,with transoceanic fiber optic cable installations reducing thecost of these networks significantly.andP;  Computer-aided softwareengineering (CASE) will quicken the pace of software developmentfor end-users.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MISFuture of ComputingTrendsConnectivityStandardizationInteroperabilityFiber OpticsComputer-Aided Software EngineeringProductivity.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>